  <description><![CDATA[ 





<section id="the-core-intuition" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-core-intuition">The Core Intuition</h2>
<p>In a deterministic, zero-sum game with perfect information (like Chess), the interests of two players are diametrically opposed. If player <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?A"> wins <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?+1">, player <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?B"> must lose <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?-1">.</p>
<p>The goal for any player is to choose a strategy that maximizes their minimum gain the <strong>Minimax</strong> value.</p>
</section>
<section id="the-mathematical-framework" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-mathematical-framework">The Mathematical Framework</h2>
<p>We define a finite zero-sum game as a triple <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?(S,%20A,%20R)">, where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?S"> is the state space, <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?A"> is the set of actions, and <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?R"> is the reward function. According to the Minimax Theorem, for any such game, there exists a value <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?V"> such that:</p>
<p><img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0AV%20=%20%5Cmax_%7Ba%20%5Cin%20A%7D%20%5Cmin_%7Bb%20%5Cin%20B%7D%20%5Cmathbb%7BE%7D%5BR(a,%20b)%5D%20=%20%5Cmin_%7Bb%20%5Cin%20B%7D%20%5Cmax_%7Ba%20%5Cin%20A%7D%20%5Cmathbb%7BE%7D%5BR(a,%20b)%5D%0A"></p>
<p>This equality is beautiful because it implies that in a state of equilibrium (a Nash Equilibrium), neither player can improve their outcome by changing their strategy unilaterally.</p>
</section>
